ODE XIV-We have already stated, in the Introductory Remarks to the fourth Ode of the present Book, that Horace had been directed by Augustus to celebrate in song the victories of Drusus and Tiberius. The piece to which we have alluded is devoted, in consequence, to the praises of the former3 the present one, to those of the latter of the two princes. In both productions, however, the art of the poet is shown in ascribing the success of the two brothers to the wisdom and fostering counsels of Augustus himself.
